{{Otheruses|Shindai characters|the Chikushi font|{{ill|Fontworks|ja|フォントワークス|zh|qq=draft|qq=draft}}}}
[[File:Chikushi Moji.jpg|thumb|Illustration of the mural in the Shigesada Kofun]] {{ill|Tsukushi Characters|ja}} (つくしもじ) are a form of {{ill|Jindai moji|ja|神代文字|fr|Jindai moji|ru|Дзиндай модзи|de|Jindai Moji|qq=draft|qq=draft}} said to be inscribed on the stone chamber of {{ill|Shigesada Kofun|ja|重定古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Ukiha, Fukuoka|ja}}, Japan. They are also referred to as Shigesada Cave Ancient Characters (Shigesada Sekkutsu Koji, '''重定石窟古字''').
== Overview == {{ill|Hirata Atsutane|ja|qq=draft|qq=draft}} recorded these characters in his 1819 ({{ill|Bunsei|ja}} 2) book *{{ill|Shinji Hinomibumi-den|ja|神字日文伝|qq=draft|qq=draft}}* (神字日文伝), listing them as "Stone Cave Characters of Chikugo Province." According to Hirata, there was a local tradition that referred to them as "characters from the age of the gods." However, he noted, *"It is difficult to ascertain whether they are truly characters."* The drawings of these inscriptions published in his work were originally obtained from a scholar of the {{ill|Kurume Domain|ja}}, passed on to Hirata through the Kokugaku scholar {{ill|Yashiro Hirokata|ja|屋代弘賢|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
Due to Hirata's influence, interest in the inscriptions grew. When {{ill|Inō Tadataka|ja}} visited Chikugo Province for surveying, he also investigated the Shigesada Kofun, conducting a detailed examination. This research, along with that of the Kurume Domain scholars, remains a valuable resource due to the scarcity of early documentation on decorated kofun.
On April 22, 1825 (Bunsei 8, 3rd month, 5th day), Kurume Domain retainers Murakami Yasutoshi and Hayakawa Issei created a detailed copy of the inscriptions. This illustration was later included in the work *{{ill|Nihon Kodai Moji Kō|ja|qq=draft|qq=draft}}* by the Kokugaku scholar {{ill|Ochiai Naozumi|ja}}. Ochiai theorized that the script was formed by combining four types of symbols with eleven additional symbols. He also noted that some dot-like marks resembled the diacritic dots used in {{ill|Siddhaṃ script|ja|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, used for indicating long vowels. Additionally, historian {{ill|Kamiya Yoshimichi|ja}} pointed out in his 1886 (Meiji 19) article *Kodaiji Kō* (*古代文字考*), published in the *Journal of the Tokyo Anthropological Society*, that similar inscriptions were found on a stone from the residence of {{ill|Matsuura Takeshirō|ja|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (formerly part of a castle wall), as well as on the {{ill|Temple bell|ja}} of {{ill|Takase Shrine|ja|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Tonami District, Etchū Province (modern-day {{ill|Nanto, Toyama|ja}}).
The *{{ill|Takenouchi Documents|ja|qq=draft|qq=draft}}* mention these inscriptions as "Yasoyo Characters" (ヤソヨ文字). According to *Shindai no Bankokushi* (神代の万国史) by {{ill|Takenouchi Yoshimiya|ja}}, these characters were created during the reign of the 22nd emperor of the Ninth Ancient Dynasty. *Nippon Ji no Hakkutsu* (につぽん字の発掘) by {{ill|Sakai Yoshio|ja|qq=draft|qq=draft}} claims they originated in the era of Emperor *Amanohihirumotoashikabikikami*, the first emperor of humanity. (For more information on the emperors mentioned in the Takenouchi Documents, see {{ill|Takenouchi Documents' List of Emperors|ja}}.)
Modern research considers these "Chikushi Characters" to be murals rather than syllabary-based writing, similar to the case of the so-called {{ill|Temiya Cave inscriptions|ja|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Hokkaido. {{ill|Hara Masaru|ja}}, in *Illustrated Guide to Shindai Characters* (*図説神代文字入門*), states: *"The attempts of Hirata and Ochiai were, in a way, akin to modern archaeology, as they sought to decipher messages left by ancient people."*
